<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="5" cellpadding="5" align="CENTER">
<tr>
<td valign="MIDDLE"><font face="Verdana" size="2" color="000000">Hate to burst your bubble but paladins are one of the hardest classes to play.  They get a bad rep as a tank who dies too quickly because most players try to play paladins as warriors.  The paladin is pretty much a warrior until level 9 and they really do change.  Get to know your spells.  Let your groups know that you will heal after the fight and that if the primary healer goes low on mana (lom) then you can back off and pick up the slack some.<p>

Trust me on this one use those heals use the yaulp and use buffs when buffs arent available.  More people will appreciate you more because most people disrespect paladins as a whole.  The reason why is by high levels people have seen so many ####y paladins die too quickly acting like pure warriors they forget the benifits of a paladin.  It like any other class with a specific role, if you have a bad cleric or bad enchanter people will die.  Same with paladins a bad paladin puts people at risk.<p>

As for equipment.  The age old debate of 1 handed vs 2 handed slash may come back, but try to max out on all weapon skills if you can.  You can never tell what weapon varant may make tommorrow to drop for paladins it may even be a piercing weapon.  But really here are the advantages to using a one hand vs 2 hand.  One hand generally means more ac and the cool shield bash which stuns casters (oh ya learn to save your bashes when you see something like an_orc_oracle begins to cast a spell.) Using bash does tip the balance.<p>

But a 2 hander gives more damage per hit (or should give more)  The more damage you do the more likely you are going to taunt if you need to use taunt to save the life of a caster being pegged.<p>

Now the important thing stats.  Work on getting the highest ac equipment you can afford, then work on your strenght, work on dex last.<br>
Agility is a nice stat but is also a trap.  Agility accually does make monsters miss you more but at level 40 or so the monsters become so powerful that pure ac begins to show its advantages over depending on agility stats.  I fell into this trap and had to scramble to earn money to buy a whole new set of armour when i reached level 42.  It wasnt pretty to say the least.  A full set of bronze or even steel plate will carry you to about level 25 but by then start changing out for more strenght buffing items and better ac.  Get yourself both a 1h and 2h by level 25 the reason is that each player will develop thier own taste of 1h over 2h and that becomes a solid personal preference by the time you are 40.  (i went with 1h cause i hate npc casters, a friend of mine went with a 2h because he wants to deal damage to tank type casters, either way is right in its own way.)<p>

Another consideration is to get your resistances up, at high levels magic using npc's have more potent spells.  Sometimes you may want to carry a box of special high ac high resistance armour pieces to change out when you go up against a camp with more casting npc's then normal.<p>

And lastly (as if i didnt ramble on already) is guilds.  Find a guild that is suited for your class.  I tend away from larger guilds for one main reason, a paladin is really a class that must bring people together.  Not only do you get a sort of commaradarie in a smaller guild but a smaller guild will be more able to accomadate a paladin when he/she is struggling on the equipment end.  For some reason a larger guild, at least to me, will tend to use thier heavy tanks more and not even consider hybrids as needing equipment, but the truth about paladins is completely different.  A paladin does need the help from his/her friends to keep his equipment up, unless of course the paladin is extremely rich.  Plus the quests for paladins are some of the hardest quests and are designed purposely to require groups with the goal to get equipment for the paladin.  And that usually means the paladin must be willing to do favours back.</font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor="DDDDDD">
