<td valign="MIDDLE"><font face="Verdana" size="2" color="000000">I Agree with most of the advice given except the on part of "dont rely on you spells". Its true in a perfect group enviroment. Chanter/warrior/Shaman,druid/and any other assortment of  tank or caster your spells will be secondary. But your melee will also be secondary to the group. a Warrior or rogue will almost always outdamage you if your on an even basis and a cleric shaman druid they will almost always out buff you. But the fact of the matter is you dont always get theese perfect groups and as you go up in levels your spells do get better when u get to the top the only heal spell you dont have is complete heal and you have always had Lay Hands. The key to playing a Paladin is realize that your a Hybrid and a Jack of all Trades. Ive been in groups that i was the Tank and we did well Ive also been in groups with 5 other tanks and played cleric sit med heal repeat we also did well. At early levels you tank at later levels you do alot of different things so learn your spells use them you will need them and you will become an asset. You go thru a constant learning curve as a paladin the higher you get the more you do. Where as a cleric has always healed and a warrior has always done the main ammount of damage and damage absorbtion. As a paladin you can and will be called on to do both considering the situation. So dont discount your spells and say im a tank because your not but learn and develop your skills as you go.</font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor="DDDDDD">
