<tr>
<td valign="MIDDLE"><font face="Verdana" size="2" color="000000">I disagree with Laurelie that said not to rely on your spells.  Paladins have great spells that will save your butt.  For example at lvl 9 tou get "Flash of Light" this spell will be a great companion through your mid teens.  If you get in over your head cast flash of light it casts quick and blinds your opponent allowing you to run away. It does not last to long but will give you a head start.  "Yalp" is also a quick cast and will increse your strength and ac for 18 seconds during which you will hit for maximum damage more often and take less damage.  Every little bit helps. <p>

I say explore your spells and use them as often as possible. Rely on them as additional skills, they will save your life.<p>

I do agree that Pally's are tank-like.  I say Tank-like because you will never be able to out damage a warrior, ranger or rogue (except maybe against the undead), however your ac could make you more desirable in a smaller group.  You will not be the primary tank at later levels, you will be asked to jump in the fray and when needed, cast on the undead, stun casters (with your stun spells), heal when necessary (hmm, spells again), and use "Lay on Hands" (thats a spell too) on a party member when things get ugly. (notice most of these involve your spells ;0))<p>

As with every class, knowing your characters strengths and limitations is essential.  You will always find a group if you play your character well within those strengths and limitations.  The key is to not be foolish and get members of your party killed because you believe that you are a tank.<p>

my 2 cp<p>

Pally</font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor="DDDDDD">
