<tr>
<td><a href="UltraBoard.cgi?Action=ShowProfile&ID=sehanine&Board=paladin&Idle=30&Sort=0&Order=Descend&Page=0&Session=" target="Profile" OnMouseOver="window.status='View Sehanine (sehanine) Profile.';return true;" OnMouseOut="window.status=''"><font face="Verdana" size="1" color="000000 ">Profile</font></a></td><td align="RIGHT"></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor="EEEEEE">
<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="5" cellpadding="5" align="CENTER">
<tr>
<td valign="MIDDLE"><font face="Verdana" size="2" color="000000">Hmmm, it's difficult on where to begin.  Alright, first I have to disagree with the people that are saying not to be proficient in 2 weapon styles.  Go with 1HS and 2HS.  You have the entire level to get each up 5 points.  Usually it takes less than a bubble to do that so just DO IT.  Why?  Because there's great weapons for both.  And you might go only 1HS and later on find that there's an incredible 2HS out there that you just HAVE to use.  And then where would you be?  1HS 200 and 2HS 50?  The Ghoulbane is a great 1HS weapon that I use as a main.  At level 40 I can deal out 57 damage a slash.  Doing double attack and a bash that can equal out to 130 a round.  And the GB is perfect for those undead things out there (and there's a lot of them).  Once you reach 20, you won't want to leave unrest for quite awhile.  Then when you get higher there's a bunch of undead everywhere else.  But I know that there's going to be a 2HS out there that I'll be green with envy to have, so I keep my skills up with my Soulfire.  And how come no one seems to mention bash?  It's a great stun for them caster creatures.  Make sure to time your bashes so that you hit them right before they start casting a spell.  It will interrupt their spell casting if the bash hits and that is always nice (especially with them healer creatures).<p>

Spells, huh.  Don't discount them.  Yaulp is my fourth hot key.  Melee attack, bash, taunt, then yaulp.  As someone said, it gives you that extra boost, and I HAVE noticed a difference in the damage of my attack.  Stun is also great when you get it at level 30.  I have the same heal as my druid friend that's close to my level, so don't discount heal either.  Who better to heal the group AFTER a fight than the paladin?  You have less mana so it's faster to recover.  Let the druid, cleric, whatever rest and get their mana back.  YOU take the initiative and heal the group as best you can.  I've had many a clerics thank me for it.<p>

DO NOT save your lay hands for yourself!  That's plain selfish.  If the cleric's in trouble, or the druid, or the enchanter, or anyONE in your group, use it on them!  If using your LoH on the druid gives him the opportunity to gate you all out of there then that benefits the whole group.  If by laying hands on the cleric gives the cleric the opportunity to heal YOU in return or, by chance if you die, you can get ressed by him, DO IT.  If someone in your group is in trouble, if it's not a mob then it's not on you, being part tank.  LoH usually turns the creature to you, which is your job in the group anyway.  I can understand about not using it on someone that's NOT in your group, but please, use it to your best advantage, which is usually someone else.  I'd rather get ressurected by the cleric, knowing that I saved the whole group, than knowing put LoH aside for when "I" needed it.  Using it on a druid especially has saved my pally hide more times than I can count.<p>

I concentrate on str stuff only because high elves tend to be weaker and armor is so dang heavy!  Only recently have I been able to get AC items and that's because my mate in game is a druid and can cast strength on me whenever I want it.<p>

My favorite area was the oasis.  For some odd reason I loved hitting the caimens and crocs.  I solo'ed myself there from 13 to 21.  Unrest is a good area for low levels to 30s.  Get a ghoulbane though.  After level 20 you'll hug it to you like your bestest teddy bear.  =)  Cyclops (in group, of course) are fun in the 30s.  There's greater skeles there too for the mid 20s.  Right now I've been doing tundra yetis for 4 levels and I'm still getting great experience at level 40.  It moves about every third yeti and that's great for a so-called "hell" level!<p>

I definitely agree with the person that says to do quests.  Half of my pally life has been quests.  Hehe  I have the Soulfire (thanks to my great friends that were bored before Kunark came out), Aegis of Life (again, thanks to my great friends although I WAS the tank for the evil Lord Grimrot - I should say thanks to the healers!), several pieces of Ro armor, Hero Bracers.......  A lot of these quests have small parts.  Small enough for low levels to start them on.  Like the Ro armor.  If you're killing dervs, save the rings and go to the named orc in South Ro and give them to him 4 at a time.  That is a minor quest you can do over and over again and it builds your Ro faction.  If you're killing skeles save the bone chips and go to the dwarven city's pally guild and hand the bone chips over to the dwarf at the end of the hall.  It builds your faction up there for parts of a lot of quests and it gives you a bit of experience.  You can even start the Soulfire quest by doing some of the little things.  =)<p>

Hope this helps!<p>

Sehanine Scherazade<br>
40th lvl Paladin, Xegony</font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor="DDDDDD">
